<br>
1) You're hopelessly awful at hand/eye coordination and motor skills. This coupled with the mental capacity of an oxygen-deprived earthworm means that you find EQ difficult to play and so you need to cheat. Well, my suggestion to you is to go out into your garden and pick out 3 equally sized rocks. Give them all a name. Then point randomly at a rock and try and remember what you called it. It'll be about the same challenge as playing EQ knowing where all the spawns are and what they're holding, I promise you. And hey. If you miss the multiplayer option, get some friends round to point at rocks with you. <br>
<br>
2) You're bored of the game and need to do something to keep interest. Some people solve this by 2-boxing, to give themselves a new lease of fun. Some people think that the boredom will be solved by making the game *even* easier by using showEQ. Some people allieviate the boredom by helping out others, playing on different rule servers etc. If you can't find interest in the game without cheating, then stop playing, delete your account and find a new hobby. Monopoly doesn't get anymore interesting when you start with hotels all over the place. <br>
<br>
3) The phrase &quot;I cheat because I can&quot;. Often followed by things like &quot;I'm a rebel without boundaries, an unstoppable anti-establishment machine. No one will be able to stop the true force of my anarchic crusade, because it's my right to rebel&quot;. Er ok mate, open your curtains and look outside at the world you no longer enter because no-one likes you. And while you're at it, you might want to turn down that nu-metal you listen to because the lyrics mirror your very existence, and make it quiet enough to hear that your mum is calling you down to dinner. She's made your favourite, because you're her &quot;Ickle lickle boy&quot;.<br>
<br>
I &quot;can&quot; go out and maim and kill and butcher and destroy, but I don't because it would spoil other people's fun. Plus I don't have time to because I'm camping Quill... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shlakor>Shlakor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#333333>(11/4/02 2:52:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7687.topic&index=91>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Can't</span><hr size=1> People keep stating that all Sony has to do is alter the EULA by adding a phrase whereby if you use the software you give up your rights and Sony can scan your machine. It does not work that way. If you signed a piece of paper stating that its ok for someone to kill you, and that person does, they still get charged for murder. Basicly, as I understand it, you cant sign away your rights. If you are protected by law, you are protected period.<br>
<br>
You know, crap like this is why we run unix/linux at work. And why my main, non game playing machine at home is linux. With linux, crap like this cant happen. Companies cant do anything illegal, they know this, and the software they put out is thought our first and not fundamentally flawed.<br>
