<br>
1. SEQ is cheating.  No matter which way you look at it, it's going against the rules which Verant laid down for the game.  As someone else said, a game is dictated by a set of rules.  If you use SEQ then you simply aren't playing Everquest.<br>
<br>
2. Plenty of people using SEQ try to rationalize it as good.  It's not.  It's still cheating no matter how many friends you help.  Most people that use it aren't twisted and evil and all that, but they aren't playing by the rules the way the rest of us are.<br>
<br>
3. Ratt behaved like a spoiled child who had his cookies taken away.  It was embarassing really.<br>
<br>
4. Verant can break SEQ any time they like by changing the memory location the key is stored in memory.  A half decent programmer could even shift it around in memory randomly, use VirtualProtect() to catch any access to it and other nasty tricks.<br>
<br>
5. It is orders of magnitude less work to break SEQ than to fix it.  While SEQ can always theoretically be fixed, if Sony decides to break things by patching the client every second day then it's going to be pretty tough on the SEQ devs sanity.<br>
<br>
6. SEQ can always be detected short of running EQ inside a complete virtual machine.  Sony doesn't even have to scan your drive for files.  As long as the memory inside EQ needs to be read to get the key out, EQ can play silly games and detect that access.<br>
<br>
Ultimately if it comes down to a battle of wills between Sony and SEQ, Sony has the edge because it take less effort to break SEQ than to fix it.  It remains to be seen how much of that pressure the SEQ devs can take but if Ratt's outburst is anything to go by...<br>
<br>
